Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Chile. The Chilean authorities authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
The FCO strongly encourage non-resident British nationals in Chile to consider leaving the country, to avoid difficulties while commercial flights remain available. For information on how to return to the UK from Chile, see Return to the UK
Entry and borders
On 18 March 2020 the Chilean Government introduced a prohibition of the entry into the country for non-Chileans. This applies to all nationalities, with the exception of non-nationals with valid residency visas for Chile.
Since 8am on 15 March, the Chilean authorities have closed all ports to cruise liners.
Local measures
Chilean President Sebastian Piñera announced a 90-day ‘National State of Catastrophe’ on Wednesday 18 March 2020.
Measures announced on Sunday 22 March include a nationwide curfew between the hours of 10pm and 5am, a quarantine around the town of Puerto Williams, ‘sanitary cordon’ around the town of Chillan and tightening of sanitary regulations for the whole of Chiloe Island. The municipal districts in Santiago of Providencia, Las Condes and Vitacura are also subject to tight controls. Further measures are expected to be announced in the coming days.
Further information
More information (in Spanish) is available on the Ministry of Health (Ministerio de Salud) website.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
